Deadly end to SWAT standoff with kidnapping suspect accused of firing at police

by Jamie Burch, ABC 7 News

Thu, February 1st 2024 at 10:09 AM
Updated Fri, February 2nd 2024 at 10:05 AM
30
VIEW ALL PHOTOS
Amarillo police said a suspect barricaded himself in the backyard of a home after kidnapping someone, holding them hostage and then firing at police (Steve Douglass/KVII)

AMARILLO, Texas (KVII) — A SWAT standoff with a kidnapping suspect accused of firing at police ended with the suspect dead.

Billy Trent Day, 31, shot himself while barricaded in a storm cellar.

Around 8 a.m., Amarillo police responded to the 4700 block of S. Virginia for a report of a person being kidnapped and held hostage overnight.

As officers arrived, they learned Day had left the scene.

About 20-30 minutes later, police encountered Day on Overlook Street, about a mile south of the kidnapping scene.

According to Chief Martin Birkenfeld, Day pulled a gun and fired at an officer.

The officer returned fire.

Birkenfeld said the officer was not hit, but they don't know if Day was injured.

After the shooting, Day ran into an alley in the 3600 block of Fleetwood.

Day fired more shots at the officer and then ran into a backyard.

Police lost sight of him.

But an officer with a drone located Day as he broke into a storm cellar and barricaded himself.

Police evacuated the house with the cellar and neighboring homes.

SWAT team negotiators spent several hours talking with Day.

During negotiations, Day continued to shoot at police.

Around 11:15 a.m., police heard another gunshot and Day quit responding.

Police forced their way into the cellar at 1 p.m. and found Day dead.

The kidnapping victim was taken to the hospital. Their condition is unknown.
